summary.seg: This manuscript, copied in the late 17th century, contains a Byzantine and patristic miscellany of excerpts and brief texts, predominantly Christian works but including some secular texts. It forms part of a two-volume set, of which the other is MS Dd.6.18, copied by the same hand. That volume contains Byzantine religious texts, with a particular interest in Church organisation. Here the focus is on theology, including scriptural commentaries and works concerning heresies and doctrinal disagreements between East and West, along with historical, geographical and scientific works.

Much of the manuscript is divided into two columns, of which one contains the text and the other notes on it, primarily recording interventions intended to correct the reading in the exemplar manuscript. Where the text is in a single column, these appear at the foot of the page. The person responsible for copying it was probably one R. Ray, the scholar at Trinity College whose ownership note, dated to 1693 and identical to a note in Dd.6.18, appears on f. i recto. This Ray currently remains unidentified, and no such person appears among the Fellows listed in Hugh MacLeod Innes, Fellows of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge 1941). He may have been a relative of John Ray (or Wray), a notable scholar and Fellow of Trinity in the mid-17th century.

support.material: Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Coat of arms ( c. 65 45 ) in the gutter, similar to Heawood 456, 458-460, 473, but including only the main motif without countermarks. These examples are dated to 1670-1713.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers i-ii + 1-91, in pencil, in Arabic and Roman numerals, recto, upper right. Every ten folios of ff. 1-91, the folio number 1, 11, 21 etc is also written in pencil, recto, lower right. On ff. i-ii, 1 the numbers 1-3 also appear in pencil, recto, lower centre and lower right, but in the latter position they have been cancelled and replaced with the numbers i-ii and 1.

collation.p: The collation could not be determined, due to the erratic distribution of watermarks and the lack of other evidence.

supportDesc.condition: There is a lateral tear in f. 26 and a tear from the fore-edge of f. 70. A single worm-hole runs througout the manuscript. There are patches of dirt and some iron-gall ink corrosion.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1v-21v A single column of 21-25 lines. 150 118
Margins ruled in red crayon.

ff. 25r-83r Two columns of 20-26 lines. The main text appears in the inner column, notes on content and emendations in the narrower outer column. 155 120
Margins and column division ruled in pencil.

handNote.p: The manuscript was copied, probably by R. Ray, in a western European mixed minuscule script imitating early printing.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, notes have been placed in the outer column of text or at the foot of the page, recording where the text has been corrected from that in the exemplar and other remarks.
An ownership note dated 1693 has been added on f. i recto: R: Ray. C.T.C. 1693, together with the classmark.

binding.p: 17th-century full leather binding, with decorative blind tooling on both boards. The classmark appears on labels on the spine, along with a blank red leather label for a title.
binding.condition: The binding has been rebacked. Both outer joints are partially split.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in the second half of the 17th century, before 1693, as indicated by the watermark and the ownership note on f. i recto. The early owner recorded by this note, R. Ray, a student or fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge, may well have copied it himself for his own use. In any case it was produced in England, as indicated by its English watermark.
history.acquisition:
Possibly presented in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 , as part of the collection of
John Moore (b. 1646, d. 1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 . This is suggested by the presence inside the left board of the bookplate used for this collection. However, this bookplate was sometimes incorrectly placed in manuscripts which did not belong to this collection, and this manuscript is not recorded as part of it in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697), nor in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore’s manuscripts, now MS Oo.7.50(2), compiled by
Thomas Tanner Tanner, Thomas, 1674-1735 .

recordHist.source: Description draws on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 1, (Cambridge, 1856), pp. 297-298.
